NYC mayor candidate Eric Adams flip-fops on Covid-19 mandates for students
     Surprise! Eric Adams, the Democratic Party candidate for Mayor of New York City, now supports mandatory Covid-19 shots for students, a 180-degree reversal of the position he expressed in the primary.  In an interview on Friday with WCBS radio reporter Lynda Lopez, Adams was asked, "If you are mayor would you mandate a vaccine for children to go to school?"

     Adams replied:  "Yes, I would. This is a city and country where we do vaccinate. I was vaccinated for smallpox, for mumps, measles and so many others. We already have a system in place that states before you start school, you receive your vaccination," Adams said. "It is to protect the child and the student population. We saw, historically, what happens when you have an outbreak of a certain type of illness that we can prevent ... so I say, "yes", if it is FDA approved, we should also mandate it, as we mandate with other vaccinations."

     Please call Adams's campaign office and his current office as Brooklyn Boro President at the numbers below and ask him why the flip-flop, and the other questions below.

     But before you do that if you value the advocacy and information brought to you by the Autism Action Network please support us in our one fundraising drive of the year by donating here.   

(929) 474-3793, Eric Adams for Mayor campaign headquarters
(718) 802-3700, Eric Adam's Brooklyn Boro President's Office 

     And please click Take Action  to send a message to Adams's campaign office

 Here are some talking points when you call. Add your own.

    Last May at the first Democratic mayoral candidate debate you indicated that you were opposed to mandatory shots for both teachers and students. Now you have flip-flopped. Why?

     Do you have any information that proves that there will be fewer deaths and illness if children get the vaccine than if they do not?  Do you have any information that shows that children are a factor in spreading Covid-19? If so, could you please send it to me and publish it on your website?

    There has been less than a year of study on the Covid-19 shots, even less on their impacts on children.  Vaccine approval usually takes anywhere from 7 to 15 years. Everyday we are learning about new side effects from Covid-19 shots. Why do you accept that these medical interventions will be safe and effective after such an extraordinarily short period of study, and when it is obvious that there is enormous political pressure to get these products to market as quickly as possible?

     People injured by vaccines had their right to go to court taken away in 1988. And vaccine manufacturers and doctors will accept no legal liability for any vaccine they administer. The federal government only accepts minimal responsibility for injury claims processed by the Vaccine Injury Compensation Program or the Countermeasures Injury Compensation Program. Why are you comfortable forcing children to undergo medical procedures where their families will bear 100% of the risk if an injury occurs?

     Adults should make medical decisions for themselves. That is as simple as, "My body, my choice." And parents should make medical decisions for their children without interference from politicians. Only six states do not allow parents to make those decisions. Five years ago, there were only two, Mississippi and West Virginia. But New York eliminated parental decision making in 2019. Do you think Mississippi is an appropriate public health model for New York? Do you agree that people should have no say in either their own or their children's medical decisions?

      I look forward to your explanation of your 180-degree change in position on this issue, and your answers to my questions. 

    Please share this message with friends and family, and please share on social networks while we still can.  Fowarded from the Autism Action Network

Regarding the size and distance of the Sun:  

‚ÄúRegiments of figures are paraded with all the learned jargon for which science is famous, but one might as well look at the changing clouds in the sky and seek for certainty there, as to expect to get it from the propounders of modern astronomy. But is there no means of testing these ever-changing never-stable speculations and bringing them to the scrutiny of the hard logic of fact? Indeed there is. The distance of the sun can be measured with much precision, the same way as a tree or a house, or church steeple is measured, by plane triangulation. It is the principle on which a house is built, a table made or a man-of-war constructed ‚Ä¶ The sun is always somewhere between the tropics of Cancer and Capricorn, a distance admitted to be less than 3,000 miles; how then can the sun if it be so many thousand miles in diameter, squeeze itself into a space of about 3,000 miles only? But look at the distance, say the professors! We have already done that and not one of the wise men we have so often challenged, has ever attempted to refute the principle on which we measure the sun‚Äôs distance ‚Ä¶ If the navigator neglects to apply the sun‚Äôs semi-diameter to his observation at sea, he is 16 nautical miles out in calculating the position his ship is in. A minute of arc on the sextant represents a nautical mile, and if the semi-diameter be 16 miles, the diameter is of course 32 miles. And as measured by the sextant, the sun‚Äôs diameter is 32 minutes of arc, that is 32 nautical miles in diameter. Let him disprove this who can. If ever disproof is attempted, it will be a literary curiosity, well worth framing.‚Äù -Thomas Winship, ‚ÄúZetetic Cosmogeny‚Äù (114-120)
